\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

object
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 far from both the source (
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

) and the observer (
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

).
 A key step in the derivation was to approximate the integrand 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(\vec{x}')=\nabla'G_{0}(\vec{x},\vec{x}')\cdot\nabla'u_{0}(\vec{x}')
\]

\end_inset

of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}u_{0}$
\end_inset

 as a constant in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and to pull it out of the integral.
 In this problem, you will carry out that process more carefully, as a Taylor
 expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\vec{x}')$
\end_inset

 around 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{1}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(\vec{x}')\approx g(\vec{x}_{1})+\left.\nabla'g\right|_{\vec{x}_{1}}\cdot(\vec{x}'-\vec{x}_{1})+(\vec{x}'-\vec{x}_{1})\cdot H\cdot(\vec{x}'-\vec{x}_{1})+\ldots
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $3\times3$
\end_inset

 second-derivative (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Hessian
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) matrix with entries 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{ij}=\frac{\partial^{2}g}{\partial x'_{i}\partial x'_{j}}$
\end_inset

.
 What we did in class was to simply keep only the 
\emph on
first
\emph default
 term in this expansion.
\end_layout

