\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 2: Crank-Nicolson vs.
 Leapfrog
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In class, we considered negative-definite discretizations 
\begin_inset Formula $A=A^{*}<0$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial u}{\partial t}=\hat{A}u$
\end_inset

 and showed that the Crank-Nicolson discretization 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\vec{u}^{n+1}-\vec{u}^{n}}{\Delta t}=A\frac{\vec{u}^{n+1}+\vec{u}^{n}}{2}
\]

\end_inset

is unconditionally stable, where the right-hand side was a way of approximating
 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}^{n+0.5}$
\end_inset

.
 Here, we will instead consider using 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}^{n+0.5}$
\end_inset

 directly.
 That is, we will imagine computing 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 at timesteps 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}^{0},\vec{u}^{0.5},\vec{u}^{1},\vec{u}^{1.5},\ldots$
\end_inset

 where we update 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 by the center-difference equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\vec{u}^{n+1}-\vec{u}^{n}}{\Delta t}=A\vec{u}^{n+0.5},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\vec{u}^{n+0.5}-\vec{u}^{n-0.5}}{\Delta t}=A\vec{u}^{n}.
\]

\end_inset

This is called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

leapfrog
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 scheme, for reasons that should become apparent (if you know the children's
 game of leapfrog).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose we are given the initial condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Outline an algorithm to update 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 successively in order to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}^{n+0.5}$
\end_inset

 for as many 
\begin_inset Formula $n>0$
\end_inset

 as desired, using the leapfrog scheme above.
 (You may need to construct a different way to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}^{0.5}$
\end_inset

.
 Preserve second-order accuracy in time!)
\end_layout

